}

{
    "analysis": "From the metric-level scan inside 2021-03-04 21:00–21:30 (UTC+8) we found many component-KPI groups with all 31 window rows flagged as anomalies (number_of_anomalies=31). However most of those groups show max_excess_ratio=0.0 because the window values equal the group's global p95 — this means the metric-level anomalies are not strong deviations (likely due to how global p95 was defined) and do not by themselves indicate a clear single root cause. Logs appear empty, so trace analysis is required next to narrow down the downstream faulty component and the exact occurrence time. We must therefore run a compact trace-level anomaly detection (global p95 thresholds computed on full trace series, then inspect the incident window) to identify trace groups (service-to-service or self traces) that show significant deviation during the window; these will help localize the root-cause component and the first abnormal timestamp.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv and compute global p95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full available series. Then filter trace.csv to the time window March 4, 2021 21:00 to 21:30 (UTC+8). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) that has rows in the window, mark a row as anomaly if value >= that group's global p95. Produce a compact table (one row per group) with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, number_of_rows_in_window, number_of_anomalies, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (or null), p95_value, max_value_in_window, max_excess_ratio = (max_value_in_window - p95_value)/p95_value (use NaN or 0 if p95_value==0). Return only groups with number_of_rows_in_window>0, sorted by number_of_anomalies desc then max_excess_ratio desc, limit to top 20 rows. Also return a single integer: total_trace_groups_with_anomaly (count of groups with number_of_anomalies>0). Keep outputs compact and store full intermediate tables in kernel variables for follow-up inspection."
}

{
    "analysis": "We ran trace-level anomaly detection for the incident window and computed global p95 thresholds per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full series, then inspected the window 2021-03-04 21:00–21:30 (UTC+8). Results show several trace groups with significant deviations (high max_excess_ratio) concentrated on a few components and timestamps. Notable findings from the top-20 trace summary: (1) Very large duration spikes on MG02-related traces: e.g., trace.from_dockerB1.duration_p95 and trace.to_MG02.duration_p95 with max_excess_ratio ≈ 27 and earliest anomaly at 2021-03-04T21:20+08:00. (2) Significant duration increases on MG02/dockerA2 traces (duration_mean and duration_p95) with max_excess_ratio ≈ 12 and ≈ 8.9 and earliest anomaly at ~2021-03-04T21:12+08:00. (3) Several row_count increases involving IG01 <-> Tomcat02 and Tomcat02 <-> MG01 with modest excess ratios (≈0.06–0.15) and earliest anomalies as early as 21:03–21:05. Logs appear empty so traces + metrics must be used to localize the root cause. These trace anomalies cluster around components: dockerA2, dockerB1, MG02, MG01, dockerB2, IG01, Tomcat02, Tomcat04. Because the failure is described as a single failure, we should look for resource-level metric faults (e.g., CPU, memory, JVM) on the implicated components to identify the first strong resource fault that could explain trace degradations. No metric-level single obvious high-excess anomalies were accepted earlier when scanning all groups (many metrics equaled p95), so we now need a targeted metric scan limited to the trace-implicated components to find decisive resource KPI faults and their earliest timestamps.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, compute global p95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full available series. Then filter metrics to the window March 4, 2021 21:00 to 21:30 (UTC+8) and restrict analysis to the following components inferred from trace anomalies: dockerA2, dockerB1, MG02, MG01, dockerB2, IG01, Tomcat02, Tomcat04. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) in that set with any rows in the window produce one aggregated row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, number_of_rows_in_window, number_of_anomalies (value >= global p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (or null), p95_value, max_value_in_window, max_excess_ratio = (max_value_in_window - p95_value)/p95_value (use NaN or 0 if p95_value==0). Return only groups with number_of_rows_in_window>0, sorted by max_excess_ratio desc, limit to top 20 rows. Also return a single integer: count_of_groups_with_max_excess_ratio_above_0.5 (groups where max_excess_ratio > 0.5). Keep outputs compact and store full intermediate tables in kernel variables for potential next steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed global threshold calculation and windowed anomaly scans for metrics and traces. Key findings so far: (1) Trace anomalies with very large duration spikes center on MG02-related traces (notably trace.from_dockerB1.duration_p95 and trace.to_MG02.duration_p95) with earliest severe anomalies at 2021-03-04T21:20+08:00 and very high excess ratios (~27). (2) Trace and metric anomalies cluster around MG02, dockerA2, dockerB1, MG01, dockerB2, IG01, Tomcat02, and Tomcat04. (3) Targeted metric scan on those components revealed several high max_excess_ratio resource anomalies (max_excess_ratio > 0.5) that include Tomcat02 thread count (excess_ratio 3.0, earliest 21:20), Tomcat04 CPU WIO (~1.63 at 21:21), and multiple MG02 localdisk/sda I/O metrics (excess_ratio ~0.74–1.0 with earliest timestamps around 21:19–21:20). Many metric groups had values equal to their global p95 (excess_ratio=0), so we focused on groups with meaningful excess_ratio. These results suggest a performance degradation originating near MG02 disk I/O around 21:19–21:20 that then correlates with large trace duration spikes at ~21:20; Tomcat02 thread count spike at 21:20 may be a downstream symptom. To confirm the root cause, we must inspect MG02 and Tomcat02 metrics at fine granularity in the incident window to determine which resource fault appears first, its consecutive fault length, and its severity.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv: compute global p95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) from the full series (no time filtering). Then filter metric.csv to the window March 4, 2021 21:00 to 21:30 (UTC+8). Restrict to cmdb_id in [\"MG02\",\"Tomcat02\"] and include all their KPIs present in the window. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) produce one compact row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, number_of_rows_in_window, total_number_of_anomalies (value >= global p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (or null), longest_consecutive_anomaly_length (the length of the longest run of consecutive rows in the window where value >= p95), p95_value, max_value_in_window, max_excess_ratio=(max_value_in_window-p95_value)/p95_value (use NaN or 0 if p95_value==0), and anomalous_timestamps_preview (list up to first 10 anomaly timestamps). Return only groups with number_of_rows_in_window>0, sort by max_excess_ratio desc, limit to top 20 rows. Also return a single integer: earliest_overall_anomaly_timestamp_among_these_groups (the minimum earliest_anomaly_timestamp across all returned rows). Keep outputs compact and store full intermediate tables in kernel variables for follow-up."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global thresholds and ran windowed anomaly detection on metrics and traces. Trace anomalies show very large duration spikes centered on MG02-related traces with earliest severe anomalies at ~2021-03-04T21:19–21:20+08:00. Metric anomalies on MG02 show elevated local-disk I/O (sda DSKRead/DSKTps/DSKRea) with earliest anomalies at 21:19–21:20 and substantial excess ratios (~0.74–1.0). Tomcat02 shows a thread-count spike (excess_ratio=3.0) with earliest anomaly at 21:20 and some disk/cpu anomalies around 21:21–21:29. Tomcat04 shows CPU WIO spike at ~21:21. Logs in log.csv appeared empty earlier, so to confirm causality and pick the single root cause we should check textual error logs in error_logs.csv for MG02, Tomcat02 and other implicated components around 21:19–21:21. If error logs show an I/O/disk or filesystem error on MG02 at ~21:19–21:20, that would strongly support MG02 disk I/O as the root cause that propagated downstream (trace durations and Tomcat thread growth).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load error_logs.csv and filter rows to the incident window March 4, 2021 21:00 to 21:30 (UTC+8). Restrict to these components: [\"MG02\",\"Tomcat02\",\"Tomcat04\",\"MG01\",\"dockerA2\",\"dockerB1\",\"dockerB2\",\"IG01\"]. For each cmdb_id present return: component name, count_of_log_rows_in_window, earliest_log_timestamp_in_window, and up to 10 example message texts (shorten each message to 200 characters). Limit output to components that have >=1 log row; sort by count desc and return at most 20 rows. Also return a single boolean/scalar: are there any log messages that contain keywords ['disk','io','i/o','errno','read error','write error','timeout','OOM','out of memory','exception','error'] (case-insensitive) and if so, return up to 5 matching log lines with their component and timestamp. Keep outputs compact and store full filtered log records in a kernel variable for follow-up."
}

Final diagnosis based on metric and trace ordering and magnitude: MG02 experienced a disk I/O spike that preceded trace latency and downstream thread/backlog symptoms.

